=========================================================
MEMBER FUNCTION THREAD (C++ INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition
----------

std::thread can execute a member function of a class.

To create such a thread, pass:

1. Pointer to the member function
2. Pointer (or reference) to the object

---------------------------------------------------------

Syntax

thread t(&ClassName::memberFunction, &object);

---------------------------------------------------------

Example

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
using namespace std;

class Test
{
public:
    void display()
    {
        cout << "Member function executed\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Test obj;

    thread t(&Test::display, &obj);

    t.join();

    return 0;
}

Output

Member function executed

---------------------------------------------------------

How It Works

thread t(&Test::display, &obj);

&Test::display
→ Pointer to member function.

&obj
→ Object on which the member function is invoked.

Equivalent to:

obj.display();

executed in a separate thread.

---------------------------------------------------------

Passing Arguments to Member Function

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
using namespace std;

class Test
{
public:
    void print(int x)
    {
        cout << x << endl;
    }
};

int main()
{
    Test obj;

    thread t(&Test::print, &obj, 100);

    t.join();

    return 0;
}

Output

100

---------------------------------------------------------

Interview Points

✓ Use &ClassName::memberFunction.
✓ Pass the object pointer/reference as the first argument after the function pointer.
✓ Additional arguments follow normally.
✓ Don't forget to call join() or detach().

---------------------------------------------------------

One-line Interview Answer

"To run a member function in a separate thread, pass a pointer to the member function followed by the object pointer (or reference) to std::thread."

---------------------------------------------------------

Memory Trick

thread t(&Class::Function, &object, args...);
